Normalization Justification:
Keeping all data in a single table may appear simple, but it introduces redundancy and data integrity issues. In the given dataset, customer, product, and sales representative information is repeated for every order. This leads to update anomalies, where changing a sales representative’s email requires updating multiple rows. Missing even one update causes inconsistency. Insert anomalies are also present. A new product cannot be added unless it is associated with an order, limiting flexibility in managing product data. Similarly, delete anomalies occur when removing an order results in the loss of related product or customer information if that record appears only once. By normalizing the data into separate tables such as customers, products, orders, and sales representatives, redundancy is eliminated. Each entity is stored once, and relationships are maintained using foreign keys. This improves consistency, reduces storage duplication, and makes updates more efficient. Therefore, normalization is essential for maintaining data integrity and scalability, rather than being unnecessary complexity.
